NVIDIA CEO Jensen Huang recently broke down AI in a way most people miss. He explained that AI is not just chatbots or models at the top. It is a full stack of layers, and every layer depends on the one below it.

AI starts with energy and physical infrastructure. Power generation, data centers, networking, and cooling systems come first. Without these, nothing else works. On top of that layer sit the chips, GPUs and accelerators that handle massive computation. Above the chips is the infrastructure and software layer that allows thousands of processors to work together at scale. Only after all of this do you get AI models. And at the very top are the applications people actually interact with.

Huang‚Äôs point is simple but critical. If the lower layers are weak or slow to build, everything above them slows down too.

He also pointed to China as an example. China, he said, can build infrastructure far faster than the United States. From factories to large scale industrial projects, timelines that take years elsewhere can be completed in record time. That speed matters in an AI race.

AI leadership is not just about having smarter models or better ideas. It is about how fast a country can build energy systems, data centers, chips, and networks. Whoever moves faster at the base of the stack gives themselves an advantage everywhere else.

AI is not a software race alone.
It is an infrastructure race.

And the countries that understand that will lead the next era.

Sundar Pichai is describing a portfolio approach to AI, not a pivot away from current models. 

Autoregressive systems still power Gemini today, but Google is actively developing diffusion models alongside them.

Diffusion represents a different set of tradeoffs. It is currently behind in capability, but it can offer speed advantages for certain tasks and may be better suited to specific problem types. 

Rather than waiting for one architecture to dominate, Google is developing several at once. This reflects uncertainty at the architectural level. 

Progress is no longer just about scaling a single paradigm, but about combining multiple approaches and using each where it performs best.
